Scalability means the ability of a system to handle increasing load (users, requests, messages) by efficiently using more resources, often without changing the code.

Elixir scales better because its concurrency model is cheap, isolated, and fault-tolerant.



First: What scalability is NOT

âŒ â€œMy code is fastâ€
âŒ â€œI add more CPU and RAMâ€

Scalability is about how the system behaves as load increases.



Ruby vs Elixir: Why scalability differs
	Ruby (Rails)

	Heavy OS threads

	Shared memory

	Locks & mutexes

	GIL limits parallelism (MRI)

	As load increases:
	â¡ more contention
	â¡ more memory
	â¡ harder coordination

Elixir

	Millions of lightweight processes
	Each process has isolated memory
	No locks

	Message passing

	As load increases:
	â¡ spawn more processes
	â¡ system stays stable

ğŸ”¹ Concrete Example (Very Important)

Scenario: 100,000 concurrent users
Ruby (typical Rails)

	Limited threads
	Requests queue up
	Memory grows fast
	Threads block each other

Elixir

1 process per connection
Lightweight (~KBs)
Scheduler manages them efficiently
System keeps responding

Interview line:

â€œElixir scales by handling more concurrent processes, not by increasing shared state.â€

